# K-means clustering
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

n_clusters = 50
model = KMeans(n_clusters)
model.fit(X)

yhat_km = model.predict(X)
clusters = np.unique(yhat_km)

k_means = {}
for cluster in clusters:
    row_ix = np.where(yhat_km == cluster)
    k_means[cluster] = [data[i] for i in row_ix[0]]
    print('Cluster >>>', cluster, '\n', k_means[cluster],'\n\n')

# SOM 

# Set the hyper parameters, num of neurons ~5*sqrt(N) = 386
num_row = 7
num_col = 7
num_iter = 5000
sigma = 1
learning_rate = 0.5

# define SOM:
som = MiniSom(x = num_row, y = num_col, input_len=len(X[0]),sigma=sigma, learning_rate=learning_rate, neighborhood_function='gaussian', random_seed=0)
#  input_len = number of features in our dataset
#  sigma = radius of the different neighbors in the SOM, default = 1
#  learning_rate = how much weights are adjusted during each iteration

# Initializing the weights
#som.random_weights_init(X)
som.pca_weights_init(X)

# Training
som.train_random(X, num_iter, verbose=True)

# each neuron represents a cluster
winner_coordinates = np.array([som.winner(x) for x in X]).T 

# convert the bidimensional coordinates to a monodimensional index
yhat_som = np.ravel_multi_index(winner_coordinates, (num_row,num_col))

clusters, counts = np.unique(yhat_som, return_counts=True)
print(counts.max(),counts.min(),counts.sum())

som_mini = {}
for cluster in clusters:
    row_ix = np.where(yhat_som == cluster)
    som_mini[cluster] = [data[i] for i in row_ix[0]]

        session.run("CREATE (c:Cluster {cluster:$cluster})",cluster=str(cluster))

    print("Num of clusters created: ", result.keys(), result.values())

    for noun, cluster in zip(data,yhat_km):
        session.run("MATCH (n:Noun {text:$noun}), (c:Cluster {cluster:$cluster}) CREATE (n) -[r:BELONG_TO]->(c) ",
                    noun=noun,cluster=str(cluster))
    
    result = session.run("MATCH p=(n)-[r:BELONG_TO]->(c) RETURN count(p) ")

# Traversing the Graph 

num_nouns = []
num_sents = []
num_docs=[]
num_comps=[]
company_names=[]

with driver.session() as session:
    
    # how many words per cluster:
    for cluster in set(yhat):
        result = session.run("MATCH p = (c:Cluster {cluster:$cluster})--(n:Noun) RETURN count(p) ",cluster=str(cluster))
        num_nouns.append(result.values()[0][0])
        
        result = session.run("MATCH p = (s:CausalSentence)-[*2]->(c:Cluster {cluster:$cluster}) RETURN count(p) ",cluster=str(cluster))
        num_sents.append(result.values()[0][0])

        result = session.run("MATCH p = (d:Document)-[*3]->(c:Cluster {cluster:$cluster}) RETURN count(distinct d) ",cluster=str(cluster))
        num_docs.append(result.values()[0][0])

        result = session.run("MATCH p = (n:Company)-[*4]->(c:Cluster {cluster:$cluster}) RETURN count(distinct n) ",cluster=str(cluster))
        num_comps.append(result.values()[0][0])

        result = session.run("MATCH p = (n:Company)-[*4]->(c:Cluster {cluster:$cluster}) RETURN distinct n.name ",cluster=str(cluster))
        company_names.append(result.values())

print('Number of nouns per cluster:', num_nouns,'\n\n')

print('Number of sentences per cluster:', num_sents,'\n\n')

print('Number of unique documents per cluster:', num_docs,'\n\n')

print('Number of unique companies per cluster:', num_comps,'\n\n')

print('Company names per cluster:', company_names,'\n\n')
